# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: riot-os
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] The 6LoWPAN group defined encapsulation, header compression, neighbor discovery and other mechanisms that allow IPv6 to operate over IEEE 802.15.4 based networks.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] Although IPv4 and IPv6 protocols do not generally care about the physical and MAC layers they operate over, the low-power devices and small packet size defined by IEEE 802.15.4 make it desirable to adapt to these layers.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] The base specification developed by the 6LoWPAN IETF group is RFC 4944 (updated by RFC 6282 with header compression, RFC 6775 with neighbor discovery optimization, RFC 8931 with selective fragment recovery and with smaller changes in RFC 8025 and RFC 8066).
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] The problem statement document is RFC 4919.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] IPv6 over Bluetooth Low Energy using 6LoWPAN techniques is described in RFC 7668.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] The targets for IPv6 networking for low-power radio communication are devices that need wireless connectivity to many other devices at lower data rates for devices with very limited power consumption.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] The header compression mechanisms in RFC 6282 are used to allow IPv6 packets to travel over such networks.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] IPv6 is also in use on the smart grid enabling smart meters and other devices to build a micro mesh network before sending the data back to the billing system using the IPv6 backbone.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] Some of these networks run over IEEE 802.15.4 radios, and therefore use the header compression and fragmentation as specified by RFC6282.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] Thread is a standard from a group of more than fifty companies for a protocol running over 6LoWPAN to enable home automation.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] The specification is available at no cost as of 24 June 2022, but paid membership is required to implement the protocol.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] Version 1.0 of the specification was published on 2015-10-29.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] The protocol most directly competes with Z-Wave and Zigbee IP.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] In IoT device communications using the Matter standard, Thread is one of two possible wireless transport layers.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] As with all link-layer mappings of IP, RFC4944 provides a number of functions.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] Beyond the usual differences between L2 and L3 networks, mapping from the IPv6 network to the IEEE 802.15.4 network poses additional design challenges (see RFC 4919 for an overview).
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] IPv6 requires the link maximum transmission unit (MTU) to be at least 1280 octets.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] In contrast, IEEE 802.15.4's standard frame size is 127 octets.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] A maximum frame overhead of 25 octets and an optional but highly recommended security feature at the link layer poses an additional overhead of up to 21 octets are for AES-CCM-128.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] This leaves only 81 octets for the upper layers.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] Since this is so much less than 1280, 6LoWPAN defines a fragmentation and reassembly layer.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] Further, the standard IPv6 Header is 40 octets long, so header compression is defined as well.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] IPv6 nodes are assigned 128 bit IP addresses in a hierarchical manner, through an arbitrary length network prefix.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] IEEE 802.15.4 devices may use either of IEEE 64 bit extended addresses or, after an association event, 16 bit addresses that are unique within a PAN.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] There is also a PAN-ID for a group of physically collocated IEEE 802.15.4 devices.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] IEEE 802.15.4 devices are intentionally constrained in form factor to reduce costs (allowing for large-scale network of many devices), reduce power consumption (allowing battery powered devices) and allow flexibility of installation (e.g. small devices for body-worn networks).
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] On the other hand, wired nodes in the IP domain are not constrained in this way; they can be larger and make use of mains power supplies.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] IPv6 nodes are geared towards attaining high speeds.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] Algorithms and protocols implemented at the higher layers such as TCP kernel of the TCP/IP are optimized to handle typical network problems such as congestion.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] In IEEE 802.15.4-compliant devices, energy conservation and code-size optimization remain at the top of the agenda.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] An adaptation mechanism to allow interoperability between IPv6 domain and the IEEE 802.15.4 can best be viewed as a layer problem.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] Identifying the functionality of this layer and defining newer packet formats, if needed, is an enticing research area.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] RFC 4944 proposes an adaptation layer to allow the transmission of IPv6 datagrams over IEEE 802.15.4 networks.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] The management of addresses for devices that communicate across the two dissimilar domains of IPv6 and IEEE 802.15.4 is cumbersome, if not exhaustingly complex.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] Several routing protocols have been proposed by the 6LoWPAN community such as LOAD, DYMO-LOW, HI-LOW.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] However, only two routing protocols are currently legitimate for large-scale deployments: LOADng standardized by the ITU under the recommendation ITU-T G.9903 and RPL standardized by the IETF ROLL working group.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] The 6LoWPAN routing scheme can be carried out in two different ways: *mesh-under* and *route-over*.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] Initially, several routing protocols were developed by the 6LoWPAN community, such as LOAD, DYMO-LOW, HI-LOW .
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] Since IP-enabled devices may require the formation of ad hoc networks, the current state of neighboring devices and the services hosted by such devices will need to be known.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] IPv6 neighbour discovery extensions is an internet draft proposed as a contribution in this area.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] IEEE 802.15.4 nodes can operate in either secure mode or non-secure mode.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] There RFC 4944 defines the IPv6 header compression mechanism for LowPAN: LOWPAN_HC1.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] It also includes compression of the UDP header over 4 bytes, but does not allow compression of the *Checksum*.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] Additionally, it restricts the range of UDP ports from 61616 to 61631 in order to compress this value to 4 bits.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] This IPv6 header compression can only be applied to local link addresses.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] To overcome this problem, an IETF LOWPAN_HC1g draft was published.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] LOWPAN_HC1g applies to global addresses for IP multi-hop communications.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] These two compression mechanisms (LOWPAN_HC1 and LOWPAN_HC1g) are complementary.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] It is therefore necessary to implement both.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] Today the proposal of the 6LoWPAN group is to use LOWPAN_IPHC.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] IPHC bytes result from compression of the IPv6 header.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] They mainly integrate information from quality of service (DSCP and ECN), next headers, number of hops and compressed source/destination addresses.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] The example below shows the increase in payload compared to the original problem (see 1re figure).
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] This payload is in the best case 70 to 75 bytes.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] Indeed, if we add the fragmentation information as indicated in the paragraph above, it will decrease to 65-70 bytes for this scenario.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] Technological developments in the 1990s (miniaturization of electronics, deployment of new wireless networks and embedded systems) enabled the emergence of new applications for sensor and actuator networks.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] With the advent of wireless technologies, the first solutions used were completely proprietary (for example Z-Wave or EnOcean).
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] With the standard IEEE 802.15.4 (radio use of wireless sensors) new proprietary standards have appeared (for example, ZigBee, WirelessHART **(in)**, etc.).
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] When first thinking about wireless sensor networking, 6LoWPAN was born from a simple idea: why reinvent a protocol when we already have IP?
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] Geoff Mulligan proposes the use of IP on 802.15.4 for sensor type equipment.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] , "robust header compression") of IETF were interested.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] A first implementation of 6LoWPAN on TinyOS released on the implementation of "Arch Rock Company: Primer Pack/IP".
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] A first implementation of 6LoWPAN on TinyOS is available on the implementation of "Sensinode Company: NanoStack v0.9.4".
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] The 6LoWPAN group publishes the RFC 4919 to ensure the interoperability of the network layer.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] There RFC 4944 sees the light of day, based on the RFC4919.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] This should allow direct connectivity to the Internet of LoWPAN equipment via IPv6 and replace them communication protocols owners like ZigBee,, which was developed after the end of the Smart Dust project.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] The IETF launches the ROLL Working Group.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] , "IP for Smart Objects"), chaired by Geoff Mulligan, is created to promote the use of IP in smart objects.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] Smart objects are small type objects switch, detector more commonly called sensors.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] To develop smart grids, President Obama announces an investment of $3.4 billion.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] Study demonstrates significant economic prospects in IoT.
[src:riot-os/6lowpan] Cisco buys the company Arch Rock (one of the leaders in BAC applications for WSN), which strengthens the strategic alliance previously signed between Cisco and Itron (metering specialist smart grid),.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] CoAP is an application-layer protocol that is intended for use in resource-constrained Internet devices, such as wireless sensor network nodes.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] CoAP is designed to easily translate to HTTP for simplified integration with the web, while also meeting specialized requirements such as multicast support, very low overhead, and simplicity.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] Multicast, low overhead, and simplicity are important for Internet of things (IoT) and machine-to-machine (M2M) communication, which tend to be embedded and have much less memory and power supply than traditional Internet devices have.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] Therefore, efficiency is very important.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] CoAP can run on most devices that support UDP or a UDP analogue.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) Constrained RESTful Environments Working Group (CoRE) has done the major standardization work for this protocol.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] In order to make the protocol suitable to IoT and M2M applications, various new functions have been added.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] The core of the protocol is specified in RFC 7252.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] CoAP makes use of two message types, requests and responses, using a simple, binary header format.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] CoAP is by default bound to UDP and optionally to DTLS, providing a high level of communications security.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] When bound to UDP, the entire message *must* fit within a single datagram.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] When used with 6LoWPAN as defined in RFC 4944, messages *should* fit into a single IEEE 802.15.4 frame to minimize fragmentation.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] The smallest CoAP message is 4 bytes in length, if the token, options and payload fields are omitted, i.e. if it only consists of the CoAP header.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] The header is followed by the token value (0 to 8 bytes) which may be followed by a list of options in an optimized type–length–value format.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] Any bytes after the header, token and options (if any) are considered the message payload, which is prefixed by the one-byte "payload marker" (0xFF).
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] The length of the payload is implied by the datagram length.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] The first 4 bytes are mandatory in all CoAP datagrams, they constitute the fixed-size header.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] This describes the datagram's message type for the two message type context of Request and Response.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] Indicates the length of the variable-length Token field, which may be 0–8 bytes in length.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] The three most significant bits form a number known as the "class", which is analogous to the class of HTTP status codes.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] The five least significant bits form a code that communicates further detail about the request or response.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] The entire code is typically communicated in the form `class.code` .
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] Used to detect message duplication and to match messages of type acknowledgement/reset to messages of type confirmable/non-confirmable.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] Every request carries a token (but it may be zero length) whose value was generated by the client.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] The server must echo every token value without any modification back to the client in the corresponding response.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] It is intended for use as a client-local identifier to match requests and responses, especially for concurrent requests.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] Matching requests and responses is not done with the message ID because a response may be sent in a different message than the acknowledgement (which uses the message ID for matching).
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] For example, this could be done to prevent retransmissions if obtaining the result takes some time.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] Such a detached response is called "separate response".
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] In contrast, transmitting the response directly in the acknowledgement is called "piggybacked response" which is expected to be preferred for efficiency reasons.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] There exist proxy implementations which provide forward or reverse proxy functionality for the CoAP protocol and also implementations which translate between protocols like HTTP and CoAP.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] In many CoAP application domains it is essential to have the ability to address several CoAP resources as a group, instead of addressing each resource individually (e.g. to turn on all the CoAP-enabled lights in a room with a single CoAP request triggered by toggling the light switch).
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] To address this need, the IETF has developed an optional extension for CoAP in the form of an experimental RFC: Group Communication for CoAP - RFC 7390 This extension relies on IP multicast to deliver the CoAP request to all group members.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] The use of multicast has certain benefits such as reducing the number of packets needed to deliver the request to the members.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] However, multicast also has its limitations such as poor reliability and being cache-unfriendly.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] An alternative method for CoAP group communication that uses unicasts instead of multicasts relies on having an intermediary where the groups are created.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] Clients send their group requests to the intermediary, which in turn sends individual unicast requests to the group members, collects the replies from them, and sends back an aggregated reply to the client.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] Research has been conducted on optimizing DTLS by implementing security associates as CoAP resources rather than using DTLS as a security wrapper for CoAP traffic.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] This research has indicated that improvements of up to 6.5 times none optimized implementations.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] In addition to DTLS, RFC8613 defines the Object Security for Constrained RESTful Environments (OSCORE) protocol which provides security for CoAP at the application layer.
[src:riot-os/constrained-application-protocol] Although the protocol standard includes provisions for mitigating the threat of DDoS amplification attacks, these provisions are not implemented in practice, resulting in the presence of over 580,000 targets primarily located in China and attacks up to 320 Gbit/s.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The **ARM Cortex-M** is a group of 32-bit RISC ARM processor cores licensed by ARM Limited.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] These cores are optimized for low-cost and energy-efficient integrated circuits, which have been embedded in tens of billions of consumer devices.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] Though they are most often the main component of microcontroller chips, sometimes they are embedded inside other types of chips too.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The Cortex-M family consists of Cortex-M0, Cortex-M0+, Cortex-M1, Cortex-M3, Cortex-M4, Cortex-M7, Cortex-M23, Cortex-M33, Cortex-M35P, Cortex-M52, Cortex-M55, Cortex-M85.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] A floating-point unit (FPU) option is available for Cortex-M4 / M7 / M33 / M35P / M52 / M55 / M85 cores, and when included in the silicon these cores are sometimes known as "Cortex-MxF", where 'x' is the core variant.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The ARM Cortex-M family are ARM microprocessor cores that are designed for use in microcontrollers, ASICs, ASSPs, FPGAs, and SoCs.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] Cortex-M cores are commonly used as dedicated microcontroller chips, but also are "hidden" inside of SoC chips as power management controllers, I/O controllers, system controllers, touch screen controllers, smart battery controllers, and sensor controllers.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The main difference from Cortex-A cores is that Cortex-M cores have no memory management unit (MMU) for virtual memory, considered essential for "full-fledged" operating systems.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] Cortex-M programs instead run bare metal or on one of the many real-time operating systems which support a Cortex-M.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] Though 8-bit microcontrollers were very popular in the past, Cortex-M has slowly been chipping away at the 8-bit market as the prices of low-end Cortex-M chips have moved downward.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] Cortex-M have become a popular replacements for 8-bit chips in applications that benefit from 32-bit math operations, and replacing older legacy ARM cores such as ARM7 and ARM9.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] In particular, the embedded wear-leveling controller inside most SD cards or flash drives is a (8-bit) 8051 microcontroller or ARM CPU.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] ARM Limited neither manufactures nor sells CPU devices based on its own designs, but rather licenses the processor architecture to interested parties.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] Arm offers a variety of licensing terms, varying in cost and deliverables.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] To all licensees, Arm provides an integratable hardware description of the ARM core, as well as complete software development toolset and the right to sell manufactured silicon containing the ARM CPU.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] Integrated Device Manufacturers (IDM) receive the ARM Processor IP as synthesizable RTL (written in Verilog).
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] In this form, they have the ability to perform architectural level optimizations and extensions.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] This allows the manufacturer to achieve custom design goals, such as higher clock speed, very low power consumption, instruction set extensions (including floating point), optimizations for size, debug support, etc.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] To determine which components have been included in a particular ARM CPU chip, consult the manufacturer datasheet and related documentation.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The architectures are binary instruction upward compatible from ARMv6-M to ARMv7-M to ARMv7E-M.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] Binary instructions available for the Cortex-M0 / Cortex-M0+ / Cortex-M1 can execute without modification on the Cortex-M3 / Cortex-M4 / Cortex-M7.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] Binary instructions available for the Cortex-M3 can execute without modification on the Cortex-M4 / Cortex-M7 / Cortex-M33 / Cortex-M35P.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] Only Thumb-1 and Thumb-2 instruction sets are supported in Cortex-M architectures; the legacy 32-bit ARM instruction set isn't supported.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] All Cortex-M cores implement a common subset of instructions that consists of most Thumb-1, some Thumb-2, including a 32-bit result multiply.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The Cortex-M0 / Cortex-M0+ / Cortex-M1 / Cortex-M23 were designed to create the smallest silicon die, thus having the fewest instructions of the Cortex-M family.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The Cortex-M0 / M0+ / M1 include Thumb-1 instructions, except new instructions (CBZ, CBNZ, IT) which were added in ARMv7-M architecture.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The Cortex-M0 / M0+ / M1 include a minor subset of Thumb-2 instructions (BL, DMB, DSB, ISB, MRS, MSR).
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The Cortex-M3 / M4 / M7 / M33 / M35P have all base Thumb-1 and Thumb-2 instructions.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The Cortex-M3 adds three Thumb-1 instructions, all Thumb-2 instructions, hardware integer divide, and saturation arithmetic instructions.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The Cortex-M4 adds DSP instructions and an optional single-precision floating-point unit (VFPv4-SP).
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The Cortex-M7 adds an optional double-precision FPU (VFPv5).
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The Cortex-M23 / M33 / M35P / M52 / M55 / M85 add TrustZone instructions.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The 16-bit Thumb-1 instruction set has evolved over time since it was first released in the legacy ARM7T cores with the ARMv4T architecture.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] New Thumb-1 instructions were added as each legacy ARMv5 / ARMv6 / ARMv6T2 architectures were released.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The Cortex-M0 core is optimized for small silicon die size and use in the lowest price chips.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The Cortex-M0+ is an optimized superset of the Cortex-M0.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The Cortex-M0+ has complete instruction set compatibility with the Cortex-M0 thus allowing the use of the same compiler and debug tools.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The Cortex-M0+ pipeline was reduced from 3 to 2 stages, which lowers the power usage and increases performance (higher average IPC due to branches taking one fewer cycle).
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] In addition to debug features in the existing Cortex-M0, a silicon option can be added to the Cortex-M0+ called the Micro Trace Buffer (MTB) which provides a simple instruction trace buffer.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The Cortex-M0+ also received Cortex-M3 and Cortex-M4 features, which can be added as silicon options, such as the memory protection unit (MPU) and the vector table relocation.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The smallest ARM microcontrollers are of the Cortex-M0+ type (as of 2014, smallest at 1.6 mm by 2 mm in a chip-scale package is Kinetis KL03).
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The Cortex-M1 is an optimized core especially designed to be loaded into FPGA chips.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] Conceptually the Cortex-M4 is a Cortex-M3 plus DSP instructions, and optional floating-point unit (FPU).
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] A core with an FPU is known as Cortex-M4F.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The Cortex-M7 is a high-performance core with almost double the power efficiency of the older Cortex-M4.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] It features a 6-stage superscalar pipeline with branch prediction and an optional floating-point unit capable of single-precision and optionally double-precision operations.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The instruction and data buses have been enlarged to 64-bit wide over the previous 32-bit buses.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] If a core contains an FPU, it is known as a Cortex-M7F, otherwise it is a Cortex-M7.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The Cortex-M23 core was announced in October 2016 and based on the ARMv8-M architecture that was previously announced in November 2015.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] Conceptually the Cortex-M23 is similar to a Cortex-M0+ plus integer divide instructions and TrustZone security features, and also has a 2-stage instruction pipeline.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The Cortex-M33 core was announced in October 2016 and based on the ARMv8-M architecture that was previously announced in November 2015.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] Conceptually the Cortex-M33 is similar to a cross of Cortex-M4 and Cortex-M23, and also has a 3-stage instruction pipeline.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The Cortex-M35P core was announced in May 2018 and based on the Armv8-M architecture.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] It is conceptually a Cortex-M33 core with a new instruction cache, plus new tamper-resistant hardware concepts borrowed from the ARM SecurCore family, and configurable parity and ECC features.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] Currently, information about the Cortex-M35P is limited, because its *Technical Reference Manual* and *Generic User Guide* haven't been released yet.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The Cortex-M52 core was announced in November 2023 and based on the Armv8.1-M architecture.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] Conceptually, it can be seen as a cross between the Cortex-M33 and the Cortex-M55.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] Key differences are that its Helium co-processor is single beat (the M55 is dual beat), and it has a 32-bit main bus similar to the M33 to ease transition of applications.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The Cortex-M55 core was announced in February 2020 and based on the Armv8.1-M architecture.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] It has a 4 or 5 stage instruction pipeline.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The Cortex-M85 core was announced in April 2022 and based on the Armv8.1-M architecture.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] The documentation for ARM chips is extensive.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] In the past, 8-bit microcontroller documentation would typically fit in a single document, but as microcontrollers have evolved, so has everything required to support them.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] A documentation package for ARM chips typically consists of a collection of documents from the IC manufacturer as well as the CPU core vendor (ARM Limited).
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] IC manufacturer datasheet for the exact physical chip.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] IC manufacturer reference manual that describes common peripherals and aspects of a physical chip family.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] IC manufacturers have additional documents, such as: evaluation board user manuals, application notes, getting started guides, software library documents, errata, and more.
[src:riot-os/cortex-m] See External links section for links to official Arm documents.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The field has evolved due to the convergence of multiple technologies, including ubiquitous computing, sensors, embedded systems, and machine learning.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Traditional fields of embedded systems, wireless sensor networks, control systems, and automation independently and collectively enable the Internet of things.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] While in the consumer market, IoT technology is most commonly as smart home products—including devices and appliances like thermostats and smart speakers—the technology's largest applications are in the business and industrial sectors.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Commercial asset tracking and fleet management represent the largest single application of IoT, accounting for 22% of the total market, driven by the need to monitor mobile assets like vehicles and shipping containers.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The largest asset tracking sub-segments in transport & logistics are trailer and intermodal container tracking, reaching 5.8 million and 5.3 million active devices globally at the end of 2024 respectively.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Other major applications include industrial monitoring, smart metering in utilities, and connected healthcare.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Due to their interconnected nature, IoT devices are vulnerable to security breaches and privacy concerns.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] At the same time, the way these devices communicate wirelessly creates regulatory ambiguities, complicating jurisdictional boundaries of the data transfer.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Around 1972, for its remote site use, the Stanford Artificial Intelligence Laboratory developed a computer-controlled vending machine, adapted from a machine rented from Canteen Vending, which sold for cash or, through a computer terminal (Teletype Model 33 KSR), on credit.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Amongst its products were beer, yogurt, and milk.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] It was named *Prancing Pony*, after the name of the room, which was named after an inn in J.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Tolkien's epic fantasy novel The Lord of the Rings.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] A successor version still operates in the Computer Science Department at Stanford, with updated hardware and software.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] While it was initially accessible only on the CMU campus, it gained prominence as the first ARPANET-connected appliance.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Mark Weiser's 1991 paper on ubiquitous computing, "The Computer of the 21st Century", as well as academic venues such as UbiComp and PerCom, produced the contemporary vision of the IoT.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The field gained momentum when Bill Joy envisioned device-to-device communication as part of his "Six Webs" framework, which was presented at the World Economic Forum in Davos in 1999.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The concept of the "Internet of things" and the term itself first appeared in a speech by Peter T.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Lewis to the Congressional Black Caucus Foundation 15th Annual Legislative Weekend in Washington, D.C., published in September 1985.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The primary defining characteristic of the Internet of things has been considered its ability to embed short-range mobile transceivers in various gadgets and daily necessities, enabling new forms of communication between people and things, as well as between things themselves.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Defining the Internet of things as "simply the point in time when more 'things or objects' were connected to the Internet than people", Cisco Systems estimated that the IoT was "born" between 2008 and 2009, with the things/people ratio growing from 0.08 in 2003 to 1.84 in 2010.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The extensive set of applications for IoT devices is often divided into consumer, commercial, industrial, and infrastructure spaces.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] A growing portion of IoT devices is created for consumer use, including connected vehicles, home automation, wearable technology, connected health, and appliances with remote monitoring capabilities.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices are part of the broader concept of home automation, which generally includes lighting, heating and air conditioning, media and security systems, and camera systems.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Moreover, long-term benefits could include energy savings by automatically ensuring lights and electronics are turned off or by making the residents in the home aware of usage.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] A smart home, also known as an automated home, could be based on a platform or hubs that control smart devices and appliances.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] For instance, using Apple's HomeKit, manufacturers can have their home products and accessories controlled by an application in iOS devices such as the iPhone and the Apple Watch.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] This could be a dedicated app or iOS native applications such as Siri.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] This can be demonstrated in the case of Lenovo's Smart Home Essentials, which is a line of smart home devices that are controlled through Apple's Home app or Siri without the need for a Wi-Fi bridge.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] There are also dedicated smart home hubs that are offered as standalone platforms to connect different smart home products.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] These include the Amazon Echo, Google Home, Apple's HomePod, and Samsung's SmartThings Hub.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] In addition to the commercial systems, there are many non-proprietary, open source ecosystems, including Home Assistant, OpenHAB, and Domoticz.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] One key application of a smart home is to assist the elderly and individuals with disabilities.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] These home systems use assistive technology to accommodate an owner's specific disabilities.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Voice control can assist users with sight and mobility limitations while alert systems can be connected directly to cochlear implants worn by individuals with hearing impairments.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] They can also be equipped with additional safety features, including sensors that monitor for medical emergencies such as falls or seizures.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Smart home technology applied in this way can provide users with more freedom and a higher quality of life.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The term "Enterprise IoT" refers to devices used in business and corporate settings.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The **Internet of Medical Things** (**IoMT**) is an application of the IoT for medical and health-related purposes, data collection and analysis for research, and monitoring.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The IoMT has been referenced as "Smart Healthcare", as the technology for creating a digitized healthcare system, connecting available medical resources and healthcare services.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices can be used to enable remote health monitoring and emergency notification systems.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] These health monitoring devices can range from blood pressure and heart rate monitors to advanced devices capable of monitoring specialized implants, such as pacemakers, Fitbit electronic wristbands, or advanced hearing aids.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Some hospitals have begun implementing "smart beds" that can detect when they are occupied and when a patient is attempting to get up.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] It can also adjust itself to ensure appropriate pressure and support are applied to the patient without the manual interaction of nurses.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Specialized sensors can also be equipped within living spaces to monitor the health and general well-being of senior citizens, while ensuring that proper treatment is administered and assisting people in regaining lost mobility via therapy as well.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] These sensors create a network of intelligent sensors that are able to collect, process, transfer, and analyze valuable information in different environments, such as connecting in-home monitoring devices to hospital-based systems.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Other consumer devices to encourage healthy living, such as connected scales or wearable heart monitors, are also a possibility with the IoT.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] End-to-end health monitoring IoT platforms are also available for antenatal and chronic patients, helping one manage health vitals and recurring medication requirements.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Advances in plastic and fabric electronics fabrication methods have enabled ultra-low-cost, use-and-throw IoMT sensors.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] These sensors, along with the required radio-frequency identification electronics, can be fabricated on paper or e-textiles for wireless powered disposable sensing devices.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Applications have been established for point-of-care medical diagnostics, where portability and low system complexity are considered essential.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] As of 2018, IoMT was being applied in the clinical laboratory industry.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] IoMT in the insurance industry provides access to better and new types of dynamic information.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] This includes sensor-based solutions such as biosensors, wearables, connected health devices, and mobile apps to track customer behavior.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] This can lead to more accurate underwriting and new pricing models.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The application of the IoT in healthcare plays a fundamental role in managing chronic diseases and in disease prevention and control.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Remote monitoring is made possible through the connection of wireless solutions.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The connectivity enables health practitioners to capture patients' data and apply algorithms in health data analysis.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT can assist in the integration of communications, control, and information processing across various transportation systems.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Application of the IoT extends to all aspects of transportation systems (i.e., the vehicle, the infrastructure, and the driver or user).
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Dynamic interaction between these components of a transport system enables inter- and intra-vehicular communication, smart traffic control, smart parking, electronic toll collection systems, logistics and fleet management, vehicle control, safety, and road assistance.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] In vehicle security applications, IoT-connected GPS trackers can operate for months or years on internal batteries, using low-power wide-area network protocols such as LTE-M to transmit location data to owners via smartphone applications when unauthorized movement is detected.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] In vehicular communication systems, vehicle-to-everything communication (V2X), consists of three main components: vehicle-to-vehicle communication (V2V), vehicle-to-infrastructure communication (V2I), and vehicle-to-pedestrian communication (V2P).
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Eventually, V2X is the first step to autonomous driving and connected road infrastructure.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices can be used to monitor and control the mechanical, electrical, and electronic systems used in various types of buildings (e.g., public and private, industrial, institutions, or residential) in home automation and building automation systems.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Also known as IIoT, industrial IoT devices acquire and analyze data from connected equipment, operational technology (OT), locations, and people.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Combined with operational technology (OT) monitoring devices, IIoT helps regulate and monitor industrial systems.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Additionally, the same implementation can be carried out for automated record updates of asset placement in industrial storage units as the size of the assets can vary from a small screw to the whole motor spare part, and misplacement of such assets can cause a loss of manpower time and money.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT can connect various manufacturing devices equipped with sensing, identification, processing, communication, actuation, and networking capabilities.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Network control and management of manufacturing equipment, asset and situation management, or manufacturing process control enable IoT to be utilized for industrial applications and smart manufacturing.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] IoT intelligent systems enable rapid manufacturing and optimization of new products and rapid response to product demands.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Digital control systems, which aim to automate process controls, operator tools, and service information systems, alongside optimizing plant safety and security, fall within the purview of the IIoT.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Furthermore, IoT can also be applied to asset management via predictive maintenance, statistical evaluation, and measurements to maximize reliability.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Industrial management systems can be integrated with smart grids, enabling energy optimization.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Measurements, automated controls, plant optimization, health and safety management, and other functions are provided by networked sensors.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] In addition to general manufacturing, IoT is also used for processes in the industrialization of construction.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] There are numerous IoT applications in farming such as collecting data on temperature, rainfall, humidity, wind speed, pest infestation, and soil content.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] This data can be used to automate farming techniques, make informed decisions to improve quality and quantity, minimize risk and waste, and reduce the effort required to manage crops.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] For example, farmers can now monitor soil temperature and moisture from afar and even apply IoT-acquired data to precision fertilization programs.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The overall goal is that data from sensors, coupled with the farmer's knowledge and intuition about his or her farm, can help increase farm productivity, and also help reduce costs.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] In August 2018, Toyota Tsusho began a partnership with Microsoft to create fish farming tools using the Microsoft Azure application suite for IoT technologies related to water management.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Developed in part by researchers from Kindai University, the water pump mechanisms use artificial intelligence to count the number of fish on a conveyor belt, analyze the number of fish, and deduce the effectiveness of water flow from the data the fish provide.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The FarmBeats project from Microsoft Research that uses TV white space to connect farms is also a part of the Azure Marketplace now.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices are in use to monitor the environments and systems of boats and yachts.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Many pleasure boats are left unattended for days in summer, and months in winter so such devices provide valuable early alerts of boat flooding, fire, and deep discharge of batteries.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Monitoring and controlling operations of sustainable urban and rural infrastructures like bridges, railway tracks and on- and offshore wind farms is a key application of the IoT.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT infrastructure can be used for monitoring any events or changes in structural conditions that can compromise safety and increase risk.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT can benefit the construction industry by cost-saving, time reduction, better quality workday, paperless workflow and increase in productivity.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] It can help in making faster decisions and saving money in Real-Time Data Analytics.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] It can also be used for scheduling repair and maintenance activities efficiently, by coordinating tasks between different service providers and users of these facilities.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices can also be used to control critical infrastructure, like bridges, to provide access to ships.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The usage of IoT devices for monitoring and operating infrastructure is likely to significantly improve incident management and emergency response coordination, and quality of service, up-times and reduce costs of operation in all infrastructure-related areas.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Even areas such as waste management can benefit.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] There are several planned or ongoing large-scale deployments of the IoT to enable better management of cities and systems.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] For example, Songdo, South Korea, the first fully equipped and wired smart city, is gradually being built, with approximately 70 percent of the business district completed as of June 2018.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] A sizeable portion of the city, the first of its kind, is planned to be wired and automated to operate with little or no human intervention.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] In 2014, another application was undergoing a project in Santander, Spain.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] For this deployment, two approaches have been adopted.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] This city of 180,000 inhabitants has already seen 18,000 downloads of its city smartphone app.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The app is connected to 10,000 sensors that enable services like parking search and environmental monitoring.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Additionally, city context information is used in this deployment, aiming to benefit merchants through a spark deals mechanism based on city behavior that aims at maximizing the impact of each notification.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Other examples of large-scale deployments underway include the Sino-Singapore Guangzhou Knowledge City; work on improving air and water quality, reducing noise pollution, and increasing transportation efficiency in San Jose, California; and smart traffic management in western Singapore.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Using its RPMA (Random Phase Multiple Access) technology, San Diego–based Ingenu has built a nationwide public network for low-bandwidth data transmissions using the same unlicensed 2.4 gigahertz spectrum as Wi-Fi.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Ingenu's "Machine Network" covers more than a third of the US population across 35 major cities including San Diego and Dallas.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] French company, Sigfox, commenced building an Ultra Narrowband wireless data network in the San Francisco Bay Area in 2014, the first business to achieve such a deployment in the U.S.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] It subsequently announced it would set up a total of 4000 base stations to cover a total of 30 cities in the U.S. by the end of 2016, making it the largest IoT network coverage provider in the country thus far.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Cisco also participates in smart cities projects.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Cisco has deployed technologies for Smart Wi-Fi, Smart Safety & Security, Smart Lighting, Smart Parking, Smart Transports, Smart Bus Stops, Smart Kiosks, Remote Expert for Government Services (REGS) and Smart Education in the five km area in the city of Vijayawada, India.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Another example of a large deployment is the one completed by New York Waterways in New York City to connect all the city's vessels and be able to monitor them live 24/7.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The network was designed and engineered by Fluidmesh Networks, a Chicago-based company developing wireless networks for critical applications.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The NYWW network is currently providing coverage on the Hudson River, East River, and Upper New York Bay.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] With the wireless network in place, NY Waterway is able to take control of its fleet and passengers in a way that was not previously possible.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] New applications can include security, energy and fleet management, digital signage, public Wi-Fi, paperless ticketing and others.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Significant numbers of energy-consuming devices (e.g., lamps, household appliances, motors, pumps, etc.) already integrate Internet connectivity, which can allow them to communicate with utilities not only to balance power generation but also helps optimize the energy consumption as a whole.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] These devices allow for remote control by users, or central management via a cloud-based interface, and enable functions like scheduling (e.g., remotely powering on or off heating systems, controlling ovens, changing lighting conditions etc.).
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The smart grid is a utility-side IoT application; systems gather and act on energy and power-related information to improve the efficiency of the production and distribution of electricity.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Using advanced metering infrastructure (AMI) Internet-connected devices, electric utilities not only collect data from end-users, but also manage distribution automation devices like transformers.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Environmental monitoring applications of the IoT typically use sensors to assist in environmental protection by monitoring air or water quality, atmospheric or soil conditions, and can even include areas like monitoring the movements of wildlife and their habitats.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Development of resource-constrained devices connected to the Internet also means that other applications like earthquake or tsunami early-warning systems can also be used by emergency services to provide more effective aid.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices in this application typically span a large geographic area and can also be mobile.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] It has been argued that the standardization that IoT brings to wireless sensing will revolutionize this area.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Another example of integrating the IoT is the concept of a "living lab." Living labs integrate and combine research and innovation processes, establishing within a public-private-people-partnership.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Between 2006 and January 2024, there were over 440 living labs (though not all are currently active) that use the IoT to collaborate and share knowledge between stakeholders to co-create innovative and technological products.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] When companies intend to implement and develop IoT services for smart cities, they need to have economic incentives.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The US government plays a key role in smart city projects; changes in policies will help cities to implement the IoT, which provides effectiveness, efficiency, and accuracy of the resources that are being used.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The Internet of Military Things (IoMT) is the application of IoT technologies in the military domain for the purposes of reconnaissance, surveillance, and other combat-related objectives.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] It is heavily influenced by the future prospects of warfare in an urban environment and involves the use of sensors, munitions, vehicles, robots, human-wearable biometrics, and other smart technology that is relevant on the battlefield.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] One of the examples of IOT devices used in the military is the Xaver 1000 system.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The Xaver 1000 was developed by Israel's Camero Tech, which is the latest in the company's line of "through-wall imaging systems." The Xaver line uses millimeter wave (MMW) radar, or radar in the range of 30-300 gigahertz.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] It is equipped with an AI-based life target tracking system as well as its own 3D 'sense-through-the-wall' technology.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The **Internet of Battlefield Things** (**IoBT**) is a project initiated and executed by the U.S.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Army Research Laboratory (ARL) that focuses on the basic science related to the IoT that enhances the capabilities of Army soldiers.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] In 2017, ARL launched the Internet of Battlefield Things Collaborative Research Alliance (IoBT-CRA), establishing a working collaboration between industry, university, and Army researchers to advance the theoretical foundations of IoT technologies and their applications to Army operations.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The **Ocean of Things** project is a DARPA-led program designed to establish an Internet of things across large ocean areas for the purposes of collecting, monitoring, and analyzing environmental and vessel activity data.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The project entails the deployment of about 50,000 floats that house a passive sensor suite that autonomously detects and tracks military and commercial vessels as part of a cloud-based network.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] There are several applications of smart or active packaging in which a QR code or NFC tag is affixed to a product or its packaging.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The tag itself is passive; however, it contains a unique identifier (typically a URL) which enables a user to access digital content about the product via a smartphone.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Strictly speaking, such passive items are not part of the Internet of things, but they can be seen as enablers of digital interactions.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The term "Internet of Packaging" has been coined to describe applications in which unique identifiers are used, to automate supply chains, and are scanned on large scale by consumers to access digital content.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Authentication of the unique identifiers, and thereby of the product itself, is possible via a copy-sensitive digital watermark or copy detection pattern for scanning when scanning a QR code, while NFC tags can encrypt communication.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] In the Internet of Things (IoT), As of April 2026, the number of devices connected and controlled via the Internet has increased.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Applications of IoT technology vary across devices, but many share common characteristics.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The IoT creates opportunities for more direct integration of the physical world into computer-based systems, resulting in efficiency improvements, economic benefits, and reduced human exertions.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] IoT Analytics reported there were 16.6 billion IoT devices connected in 2023.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] In 2020, the same firm projected there would be 30 billion devices connected by 2025.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] As of October, 2024, there are around 17 billion.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Ambient intelligence and autonomous control are not part of the original concept of the Internet of things.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Ambient intelligence and autonomous control do not necessarily require Internet structures, either.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] However, there is a shift in research (by companies such as Intel) to integrate the concepts of the IoT and autonomous control, with initial outcomes towards this direction considering objects as the driving force for autonomous IoT.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] An approach in this context is deep reinforcement learning where most of IoT systems provide a dynamic and interactive environment.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Training an agent (i.e., IoT device) to behave smartly in such an environment cannot be addressed by conventional machine learning algorithms such as supervised learning.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Through a reinforcement learning approach, a learning agent can sense the environment's state (e.g., sensing home temperature), perform actions (e.g., turn HVAC on or off) and learn by maximizing accumulated rewards it receives.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] IoT intelligence can be offered at three levels: IoT devices, Edge/Fog nodes, and cloud computing.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The need for intelligent control and decision at each level depends on the time sensitiveness of the IoT application.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] For example, an autonomous vehicle's camera needs to make real-time obstacle detection to avoid an accident.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] This fast decision making would not be possible if it is necessary to transfer data from the vehicle to cloud instances and return the predictions back to the vehicle.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Instead, the operation should be performed locally in the vehicle.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Integrating advanced machine learning algorithms, including deep learning, into IoT devices is an active research area to make smart objects closer to reality.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Moreover, it is possible to get the most value out of IoT deployments through analyzing IoT data, extracting hidden information, and predicting control decisions.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] A wide variety of machine learning techniques have been used in IoT domain ranging from traditional methods such as regression, support vector machine, and random forest to advanced ones such as convolutional neural networks, LSTM, and variational autoencoder.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Modern IoT products and solutions in the marketplace use a variety of different technologies to support such context-aware automation, but more sophisticated forms of intelligence are requested to permit sensor units and intelligent cyber-physical systems to be deployed in real environments.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] IoT system architecture, in its simplistic view, consists of three tiers: Tier 1: Devices, Tier 2: the Edge Gateway, and Tier 3: the Cloud.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Devices include networked things, such as the sensors and actuators found in IoT equipment, particularly those that use protocols such as Modbus, Bluetooth, Zigbee, or proprietary protocols, to connect to an Edge Gateway.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The Edge Gateway layer consists of sensor data aggregation systems called Edge Gateways that provide functionality, such as pre-processing of the data, securing connectivity to cloud, using systems such as WebSockets, the event hub, and, even in some cases, edge analytics or fog computing.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Edge Gateway layer is also required to give a common view of the devices to the upper layers to facilitate in easier management.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The final tier includes the cloud application built for IoT using the microservices architecture, which are usually polyglot and inherently secure in nature using HTTPS/OAuth.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] It includes various database systems that store sensor data, such as time series databases or asset stores using backend data storage systems (e.g.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The cloud tier in most cloud-based IoT system features event queuing and messaging system that handles communication that transpires in all tiers.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Some experts classified the three-tiers in the IoT system as edge, platform, and enterprise and these are connected by proximity network, access network, and service network, respectively.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] IoT requires huge scalability in the network space to handle the surge of devices.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] IETF 6LoWPAN can be used to connect devices to IP networks.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] With billions of devices being added to the Internet space, IPv6 may play an important role in handling the network layer scalability.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] IETF's Constrained Application Protocol, ZeroMQ, and MQTT can provide lightweight data transport.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] In practice, many groups of IoT devices are hidden behind gateway nodes and may not have unique addresses.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Also, the vision of everything being interconnected is not needed for most applications as it is mainly the data that needs interconnecting at a higher layer.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Fog computing is a viable alternative to prevent such a large burst of data flow through the Internet.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The edge devices' computation power to analyze and process data is extremely limited.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Limited processing power is a key attribute of IoT devices as their purpose is to supply data about physical objects while remaining autonomous.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Heavy processing requirements use more battery power, harming IoT's ability to operate.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Scalability is easy because IoT devices simply supply data through the Internet to a server with sufficient processing power.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Performance is improved, especially for huge IoT systems with millions of nodes.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Conventional IoT is connected via a mesh network and led by a major head node (centralized controller).
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The head node decides how a data is created, stored, and transmitted.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] In contrast, decentralized IoT attempts to divide IoT systems into smaller divisions.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The head node authorizes partial decision-making power to lower level sub-nodes under mutual agreed policy.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Some approaches to decentralized IoT attempt to address the limited bandwidth and hashing capacity of battery-powered or wireless IoT devices via blockchain.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] In semi-open or closed loops (i.e., value chains, whenever a global finality can be settled) the IoT is often analyzed as a complex system due to the large number of different interactions between autonomous actors, and its capacity to integrate new actors.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] At the overall stage (full open loop) it will likely be seen as a chaotic environment (since systems always have finality).
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] As a practical approach, not all elements on the Internet of things run in a global, public space.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Subsystems are often implemented to mitigate the risks of privacy, control and reliability.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] For example, domestic robotics (domotics) running inside a smart home might only share data within and be available via a local network.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Managing and controlling a high dynamic ad hoc IoT things/devices network is a complex task within traditional network architecture, software-defined networking (SDN) provides a dynamic approach that better fits the special requirements of IoT applications.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The exact scale of the Internet of things is unknown, with quotes of billions or trillions often quoted at the beginning of IoT articles.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] In 2015, there were 83 million smart devices in people's homes.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] This number is expected to grow to 193 million devices by 2020.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] In 2023, the number of connected IoT devices will reach 16.6 billion.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] The number of online-capable devices grew 31% from 2016 to 2017 to reach 8.4 billion.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] In the Internet of things, the precise geographic location of a thing—and also the precise geographic dimensions of a thing—can be critical.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] (Note that some things on the Internet of things will be sensors, and sensor location is usually important.) The GeoWeb and Digital Earth are applications that become possible when things can become organized and connected by location.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] However, the challenges that remain include the constraints of variable spatial scales, the need to handle massive amounts of data, and an indexing for fast search and neighbour operations.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] On the Internet of things, if things are able to take actions on their own initiative, this human-centric mediation role is eliminated.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Thus, the time-space context that we as humans take for granted must be given a central role in this information ecosystem.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Just as standards play a key role on the Internet and the Web, geo-spatial standards will play a key role on the Internet of things.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Many IoT devices have the potential to take a piece of this market.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] For improved user interaction, some technology leaders are joining forces to create standards for communication between devices to solve this problem.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Others are turning to the concept of predictive interaction of devices, "where collected data is used to predict and trigger actions on the specific devices" while making them work together.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Social Internet of things (SIoT) is a new kind of IoT that focuses on the importance of social interaction and relationships between IoT devices.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] IoT defines a device with an identity like a citizen in a community and connects them to the Internet to provide services to its users.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] SIoT defines a social network for IoT devices only to interact with each other for different goals that to serve human.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] SIoT is different from the original IoT in terms of the collaboration characteristics.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] IoT is passive; it was set to serve for dedicated purposes with existing IoT devices in a predetermined system.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] SIoT is active, it was programmed and managed by AI to serve for unplanned purposes with mix and match of potential IoT devices from different systems that benefit its users.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] IoT devices with built-in sociability are able to broadcast their abilities or functionality, which can be used to discover and share information with other IoT devices in the same or nearby network, realizing SIoT.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Facilitating further functionality with these abilities could be helpful during emergencies.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] IoT sensors on the vehicles, road and traffic lights monitor the conditions of the vehicles and drivers and alert when attention is needed, and also coordinate themselves automatically to ensure autonomous driving is working normally.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] If a crash happens, the IoT camera will inform the nearest hospital and police station for help.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] System security is always a concern for any technology, and it is more crucial for SIoT as not only the security of oneself needs to be considered, but also the mutual trust mechanism between collaborative IoT devices from time to time, from place to place.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] Another critical challenge for SIoT is the accuracy and reliability of the sensors.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p01] In most circumstances, IoT sensors would need to respond quickly to avoid accidents, injury, and loss of life.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] There are many technologies that enable the IoT.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] The original idea of the Auto-ID Center is based on RFID tags and distinct identification through the Electronic Product Code.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] This has evolved into objects having an IP address or URI.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] An alternative view, from the world of the Semantic Web focuses instead on making all things (not just those electronic, smart, or RFID-enabled) addressable by the existing naming protocols, such as URI.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] The objects themselves do not converse, but they may now be referred to by other agents, such as powerful centralised servers acting for their human owners.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Integration with the Internet implies that devices will use an IP address as a distinct identifier.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Due to the limited address space of IPv4 (which allows for 4.3 billion different addresses), objects in the IoT will have to use the next generation of the Internet protocol (IPv6) to scale to the extremely large address space required.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Internet-of-things devices additionally will benefit from the stateless address auto-configuration present in IPv6, as it reduces the configuration overhead on the hosts, and the IETF 6LoWPAN header compression.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] To a large extent, the future of the Internet of things will not be possible without the support of IPv6; and consequently, the global adoption of IPv6 in the coming years will be critical for the successful development of the IoT in the future.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Different technologies have different roles in a protocol stack.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] This is a list of technical standards for the IoT, most of which are open standards, and the standards organizations that aspire to successfully setting them.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Some scholars and activists argue that the IoT can be used to create new models of civic engagement if device networks can be open to user control and interoperable platforms.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Howard, a professor and author, writes that political life in both democracies and authoritarian regimes will be shaped by the way the IoT will be used for civic engagement.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] For that to happen, he argues that any connected device should be able to divulge a list of the "ultimate beneficiaries" of its sensor data and that individual citizens should be able to add new organisations to the beneficiary list.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] In addition, he argues that civil society groups need to start developing their IoT strategy for making use of data and engaging with the public.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] One of the key drivers of the IoT is data.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] The success of the idea of connecting devices to make them more efficient is dependent upon access to and storage & processing of data.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] For this purpose, companies working on the IoT collect data from multiple sources and store it in their cloud network for further processing.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] This leaves the door wide open for privacy and security dangers and single point vulnerability of multiple systems.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] The other issues pertain to consumer choice and ownership of data and how it is used.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Though still in their infancy, regulations and governance regarding these issues of privacy, security, and data ownership continue to develop.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Some examples of legislation that is relevant to privacy and data collection are: the US Privacy Act of 1974, OECD Guidelines on the Protection of Privacy and Transborder Flows of Personal Data of 1980, and the EU Directive 95/46/EC of 1995.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] However, the FTC stopped at just making recommendations for now.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] A resolution passed by the Senate in March 2015, is already being considered by the Congress.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] This resolution recognized the need for formulating a National Policy on IoT and the matter of privacy, security and spectrum.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Approved on 28 September 2018, California Senate Bill No.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Several standards for the IoT industry are actually being established relating to automobiles because most concerns arising from use of connected cars apply to healthcare devices as well.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] In fact, the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) is preparing cybersecurity guidelines and a database of best practices to make automotive computer systems more secure.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] A recent report from the World Bank examines the challenges and opportunities in government adoption of IoT.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] In early December 2021, the U.K. government introduced the Product Security and Telecommunications Infrastructure bill (PST), an effort to legislate IoT distributors, manufacturers, and importers to meet certain cybersecurity standards.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] The bill also seeks to improve the security credentials of consumer IoT devices.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] For example, wireless connectivity for IoT devices can be done using Bluetooth, Wi-Fi, Wi-Fi HaLow, Zigbee, Z-Wave, LoRa, NB-IoT, Cat M1 as well as completely custom proprietary radios – each with its own advantages and disadvantages; and unique support ecosystem.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] The IoT's amorphous computing nature is also a problem for security, since patches to bugs found in the core operating system often do not reach users of older and lower-price devices.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] One set of researchers says that the failure of vendors to support older devices with patches and updates leaves more than 87% of active Android devices vulnerable.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Howard, a professor and author, writes that the Internet of things offers immense potential for empowering citizens, making government transparent, and broadening information access.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Howard cautions, however, that privacy threats are enormous, as is the potential for social control and political manipulation.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Concerns about privacy have led many to consider the possibility that big data infrastructures such as the Internet of things and data mining are inherently incompatible with privacy.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Key challenges of increased digitalization in the water, transport or energy sector are related to privacy and cybersecurity which necessitate an adequate response from research and policymakers alike.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Writer Adam Greenfield claims that IoT technologies are not only an invasion of public space but are also being used to perpetuate normative behavior, citing an instance of billboards with hidden cameras that tracked the demographics of passersby who stopped to read the advertisement.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] The Internet of Things Council compared the increased prevalence of digital surveillance due to the Internet of things to the concept of the panopticon described by Jeremy Bentham in the 18th century.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] The assertion is supported by the works of French philosophers Michel Foucault and Gilles Deleuze.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] In *Discipline and Punish: The Birth of the Prison*, Foucault asserts that the panopticon was a central element of the discipline society developed during the Industrial Era.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Foucault also argued that the discipline systems established in factories and school reflected Bentham's vision of panopticism.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] In his 1992 paper "Postscripts on the Societies of Control", Deleuze wrote that the discipline society had transitioned into a control society, with the computer replacing the panopticon as an instrument of discipline and control while still maintaining the qualities similar to that of panopticism.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Peter-Paul Verbeek, a professor of philosophy of technology at the University of Twente, Netherlands, writes that technology already influences our moral decision making, which in turn affects human agency, privacy and autonomy.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] He cautions against viewing technology merely as a human tool and advocates instead to consider it as an active agent.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Tim O'Reilly believes that the way companies sell IoT devices to consumers is misplaced, disputing the notion that the IoT is about gaining efficiency from putting all kinds of devices online and postulating that, "IoT is really about human augmentation.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Editorials at WIRED have also expressed concern, one stating, "What you're about to lose is your privacy.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) expressed concern regarding the ability of IoT to erode people's control over their own lives.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] The ACLU wrote that "There's simply no way to forecast how these immense powers – disproportionately accumulating in the hands of corporations seeking financial advantage and governments craving ever more control – will be used.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] In response to rising concerns about privacy and smart technology, in 2007, the British Government stated it would follow formal Privacy by Design principles when implementing its smart metering program.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] The program would lead to the replacement of traditional power meters with smart power meters, which could track and manage energy usage more accurately.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] However the British Computer Society is doubtful these principles were ever actually implemented.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] In 2009, the Dutch Parliament rejected a similar smart metering program, basing their decision on privacy concerns.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] The Dutch program later revised and passed in 2011.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] A challenge for producers of IoT applications is to clean, process and interpret the vast amount of data that is gathered by the sensors.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] There is a solution proposed for the analytics of the information referred to as Wireless Sensor Networks.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] These networks share data among sensor nodes that are sent to a distributed system for the analytics of the sensory data.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Another challenge is the storage of this bulk data.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Depending on the application, there could be high data acquisition requirements, which in turn lead to high storage requirements.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] In 2013, the Internet was estimated to be responsible for consuming 5% of the total energy produced, and a "daunting challenge to power" IoT devices to collect and even store data still remains.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Data silos, although a common challenge of legacy systems, still commonly occur with the implementation of IoT devices, particularly within manufacturing.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] As there are a lot of benefits to be gained from IoT and IIoT devices, the means in which the data is stored can present serious challenges without the principles of autonomy, transparency, and interoperability being considered.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] The challenges do not occur by the device itself, but the means in which databases and data warehouses are set up.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] These challenges were identified by Keller (2021) when investigating the IT and application landscape of I4.0 implementation within German M&E manufacturers.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Security is the biggest concern in adopting Internet of things technology, with concerns that rapid development is happening without appropriate consideration of the profound security challenges involved and the regulatory changes that might be necessary.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] The rapid development of the Internet of Things (IoT) has allowed billions of devices to connect to the network.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Due to too many connected devices and the limitation of communication security technology, various security issues gradually appear in the IoT.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Most of the technical security concerns are similar to those of conventional servers, workstations and smartphones.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] These concerns include using weak authentication, forgetting to change default credentials, unencrypted messages sent between devices, SQL injections, man-in-the-middle attacks, and poor handling of security updates.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] However, many IoT devices have severe operational limitations on the computational power available to them.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] These constraints often make them unable to directly use basic security measures such as implementing firewalls or using strong cryptosystems to encrypt their communications with other devices - and the low price and consumer focus of many devices makes a robust security patching system uncommon.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Rather than conventional security vulnerabilities, fault injection attacks are on the rise and targeting IoT devices.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] A fault injection attack is a physical attack on a device to purposefully introduce faults in the system to change the intended behavior.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Faults might happen unintentionally due to environmental noises and electromagnetic fields.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] There are ideas stemming from control-flow integrity (CFI) to prevent fault injection attacks and system recovery to a healthy state before the fault.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Computer-controlled devices in automobiles such as brakes, engine, locks, hood and trunk releases, horn, heat, and dashboard have been shown to be vulnerable to attackers who have access to the on-board network.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] In some cases, vehicle computer systems are Internet-connected, allowing them to be exploited remotely.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] By 2008, security researchers had shown the ability to remotely control pacemakers without authority.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Later, hackers demonstrated remote control of insulin pumps and implantable cardioverter defibrillators.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Poorly secured Internet-accessible IoT devices can also be subverted to attack others.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] In 2016, a distributed denial of service attack powered by Internet of things devices running the Mirai malware took down a DNS provider and major web sites.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] The Mirai Botnet had infected roughly 65,000 IoT devices within the first 20 hours.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Eventually, the infections increased to around 200,000 to 300,000 infections.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Brazil, Colombia and Vietnam made up of 41.5% of the infections.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] The Mirai Botnet had singled out specific IoT devices that consisted of DVRs, IP cameras, routers and printers.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] These sorts of attacks have caused security experts to view IoT as a real threat to Internet services.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] National Intelligence Council in an unclassified report maintains that it would be hard to deny "access to networks of sensors and remotely-controlled objects by enemies of the United States, criminals, and mischief makers...
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] An open market for aggregated sensor data could serve the interests of commerce and security no less than it helps criminals and spies identify vulnerable targets.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Thus, massively parallel sensor fusion may undermine social cohesion, if it proves to be fundamentally incompatible with Fourth-Amendment guarantees against unreasonable search." In general, the intelligence community views the Internet of things as a rich source of data.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] There have been a range of responses to concerns over security.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] The Internet of Things Security Foundation (IoTSF) was launched on 23 September 2015 with a mission to secure the Internet of things by promoting knowledge and best practices.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Its founding board is made up of technology providers and telecommunications companies.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] In addition, large IT companies are continually developing innovative solutions to ensure the security of IoT devices.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] In 2017, Mozilla launched Project Things, which allows to route IoT devices through a safe Web of Things gateway.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] As per the estimates from KBV Research, the overall IoT security market would grow at 27.9% rate during 2016–2022 as a result of growing infrastructural concerns and diversified usage of Internet of things.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Governmental regulation is argued by some to be necessary to secure IoT devices and the wider Internet – as market incentives to secure IoT devices is insufficient.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] It was found that due to the nature of most of the IoT development boards, they generate predictable and weak keys which make it easy to be utilized by man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] However, various hardening approaches were proposed by many researchers to resolve the issue of SSH weak implementation and weak keys.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] IoT security within the field of manufacturing presents different challenges and varying perspectives.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Within the EU and Germany, data protection is constantly referenced throughout manufacturing and digital policy, particularly that of I4.0.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] However, the attitude towards data security differs from the enterprise perspective, whereas there is an emphasis on less data protection in the form of GDPR, as the data being collected from IoT devices in the manufacturing sector does not display personal details.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Yet, research has indicated that manufacturing experts are concerned about "data security for protecting machine technology from international competitors with the ever-greater push for interconnectivity".
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] IoT systems are typically controlled by event-driven smart apps that take as input either sensed data, user inputs, or other external triggers (from the Internet) and command one or more actuators towards providing different forms of automation.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Examples of sensors include smoke detectors, motion sensors, and contact sensors.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Examples of actuators include smart locks, smart power outlets, and door controls.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Popular control platforms on which third-party developers can build smart apps that interact wirelessly with these sensors and actuators include Samsung's SmartThings, Apple's HomeKit, and Amazon's Alexa, among others.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Detecting flaws that lead to such states, requires a holistic view of installed apps, component devices, their configurations, and more importantly, how they interact.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Recently, researchers from the University of California Riverside have proposed IotSan, a novel practical system that uses model checking as a building block to reveal "interaction-level" flaws by identifying events that can lead the system to unsafe states.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] They have evaluated IotSan on the Samsung SmartThings platform.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] From 76 manually configured systems, IotSan detects 147 vulnerabilities (i.e., violations of safe physical states/properties).
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Given widespread recognition of the evolving nature of the design and management of the Internet of things, sustainable and secure deployment of IoT solutions must design for "anarchic scalability".
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Application of the concept of anarchic scalability can be extended to physical systems (i.e. controlled real-world objects), by virtue of those systems being designed to account for uncertain management futures.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] This hard anarchic scalability thus provides a pathway forward to fully realize the potential of Internet-of-things solutions by selectively constraining physical systems to allow for all management regimes without risking physical failure.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Brown University computer scientist Michael Littman has argued that successful execution of the Internet of things requires consideration of the interface's usability as well as the technology itself.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] A concern regarding Internet-of-things technologies pertains to the environmental impacts of the manufacture, use, and eventual disposal of all these semiconductor-rich devices.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Modern electronics are replete with a wide variety of heavy metals and rare-earth metals, as well as highly toxic synthetic chemicals.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] This makes them extremely difficult to properly recycle.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Electronic components are often incinerated or placed in regular landfills.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Furthermore, the human and environmental cost of mining the rare-earth metals that are integral to modern electronic components continues to grow.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] This leads to societal questions concerning the environmental impacts of IoT devices over their lifetime.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] The Electronic Frontier Foundation has raised concerns that companies can use the technologies necessary to support connected devices to intentionally disable or "brick" their customers' devices via a remote software update or by disabling a service necessary to the operation of the device.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] In one example, home automation devices sold with the promise of a "Lifetime Subscription" were rendered useless after Nest Labs acquired Revolv and made the decision to shut down the central servers the Revolv devices had used to operate.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Owners should be free to point their devices to a different server or collaborate on improved software.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] But such action violates the United States DMCA section 1201, which only has an exemption for "local use".
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] This forces tinkerers who want to keep using their own equipment into a legal grey area.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] EFF thinks buyers should refuse electronics and software that prioritize the manufacturer's wishes above their own.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Examples of post-sale manipulations include Google Nest Revolv, disabled privacy settings on Android, Sony disabling Linux on PlayStation 3, and enforced EULA on Wii U.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Kevin Lonergan at *Information Age*, a business technology magazine, has referred to the terms surrounding the IoT as a "terminology zoo".
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] The lack of clear terminology is not "useful from a practical point of view" and a "source of confusion for the end user".
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] A company operating in the IoT space could be working in anything related to sensor technology, networking, embedded systems, or analytics.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Regarding IIoT, an industrial sub-field of IoT, the Industrial Internet Consortium's Vocabulary Task Group has created a "common and reusable vocabulary of terms" to ensure "consistent terminology" across publications issued by the Industrial Internet Consortium.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] IoT One has created an IoT Terms Database including a New Term Alert to be notified when a new term is published.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] As of March 2020, this database aggregates 807 IoT-related terms, while keeping material "transparent and comprehensive".
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Despite a shared belief in the potential of the IoT, industry leaders and consumers are facing barriers to adopting IoT technology more widely.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Mike Farley argued in Forbes that while IoT solutions appeal to early adopters, they either lack interoperability or a clear use case for end-users.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] A study by Ericsson regarding the adoption of IoT among Danish companies suggests that many struggle "to pinpoint exactly where the value of IoT lies for them".
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] As for IoT, especially in regard to consumer IoT, information about a user's daily routine is collected so that the "things" around the user can cooperate to provide better services that fulfill personal preferences.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] When the collected information which describes a user in detail travels through multiple hops in a network, due to a diverse integration of services, devices and network, the information stored on a device is vulnerable to privacy violation by compromising nodes existing in an IoT network.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] For example, on 21 October 2016, a multiple distributed denial of service (DDoS) attacks systems operated by domain name system provider Dyn, which caused the inaccessibility of several websites, such as GitHub, Twitter, and others.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] This attack is executed through a botnet consisting of a large number of IoT devices including IP cameras, gateways, and even baby monitors.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Information privacy regulations also require organisations to practice "reasonable security".
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] As each organisation's environment is unique, it can prove challenging to demonstrate what "reasonable security" is and what potential risks could be involved for the business.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] According to antivirus provider Kaspersky, there were 639 million data breaches of IoT devices in 2020 and 1.5 billion breaches in the first six months of 2021.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] One method of overcoming the barrier of safety issues is the introduction of standards and certification of devices.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] In 2024, two voluntary and non-competing programs were proposed and launched in the United States: the US Cyber Trust Mark from The Federal Communications Commission and CSA's IoT Device Security Specification from the Connectivity Standards Alliance.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] The programs incorporate international expertise, with the CSA mark recognized by the Singapore Cybersecurity Agency.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Compliance means that IoT devices can resist hacking, control hijacking and theft of confidential data.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Some of these companies risk being "kodaked" – "Kodak was a market leader until digital disruption eclipsed film photography with digital photos" – failing to "see the disruptive forces affecting their industry" and "to truly embrace the new business models the disruptive change opens up".
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] According to a 2018 study, 70–75% of IoT deployments were stuck in the pilot or prototype stage, unable to reach scale due in part to a lack of business planning.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Even though scientists, engineers, and managers across the world are continuously working to create and exploit the benefits of IoT products, there are some flaws in the governance, management and implementation of such projects.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Despite tremendous forward momentum in the field of information and other underlying technologies, IoT still remains a complex area and the problem of how IoT projects are managed still needs to be addressed.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] IoT projects must be run differently than simple and traditional IT, manufacturing or construction projects.
[src:riot-os/internet-of-things-p02] Because IoT projects have longer project timelines, a lack of skilled resources and several security/legal issues, there is a need for new and specifically designed project processes.
[src:riot-os/riot-operating-system] It was initially developed by Free University of Berlin (FU Berlin), French Institute for Research in Computer Science and Automation (INRIA) and the Hamburg University of Applied Sciences (HAW Hamburg).
[src:riot-os/riot-operating-system] RIOT's kernel is mostly inherited from FireKernel, which was originally developed for sensor networks.
[src:riot-os/riot-operating-system] In 2015, one of the co-developers, Matthias Wählisch was awarded the Young Scientist Award of the Forum for Excellent Young Scientists for the contributions of his team to the open source operating system RIOT.
[src:riot-os/riot-operating-system] In 2016, the ED STIC Doctoral Prize 2017 of the University of Paris-Saclay was awarded to another co-founder, Oliver Hahm for his contribution to the project.
[src:riot-os/riot-operating-system] RIOT is based on a microkernel architecture.
[src:riot-os/riot-operating-system] In contrast to other operating systems with similarly low memory use (such as TinyOS or Contiki), RIOT allows application software programming with the programming languages C and C++, and Rust, also by an experimental application programming interface (API).
[src:riot-os/riot-operating-system] It has full multithreading and real-time abilities.
[src:riot-os/riot-operating-system] Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) and successor Transport Layer Security (TLS) are supported by popular libraries such as wolfSSL.
[src:riot-os/riot-operating-system] RIOT runs on processors of 8 bits (such as AVR Atmega), 16 bits (such as TI MSP430), and 32 bits (such as ARM Cortex).
[src:riot-os/riot-operating-system] A native port also enables RIOT to run as a Linux or macOS process, enabling use of standard developing and debugging tools such as GNU Compiler Collection (GCC), GNU Debugger, Valgrind, Wireshark, etc.
[src:riot-os/riot-operating-system] RIOT is partly Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX) compliant.
[src:riot-os/riot-operating-system] RIOT provides multiple network stacks, including IPv6, 6LoWPAN, or content centric networking and standard protocols such as RPL, User Datagram Protocol (UDP), Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), and CoAP.
[src:riot-os/riot-operating-system] RIOT source code is available on GitHub, and developed by an international community of open source developers.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] These are similar to wireless ad hoc networks in the sense that they rely on wireless connectivity and spontaneous formation of networks so that sensor data can be transported wirelessly.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] WSNs monitor physical conditions, such as temperature, sound, and pressure.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Modern networks are bi-directional, both collecting data and enabling control of sensor activity.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] The development of these networks was motivated by military applications such as battlefield surveillance.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Such networks are used in industrial and consumer applications, such as industrial process monitoring and control and machine health monitoring and agriculture.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] A WSN is built of "nodes" – from a few to hundreds or thousands, where each node is connected to other sensors.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Each such node typically has several parts: a radio transceiver with an internal antenna or connection to an external antenna, a microcontroller, an electronic circuit for interfacing with the sensors and an energy source, usually a battery or an embedded form of energy harvesting.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] A sensor node might vary in size from a shoebox to (theoretically) a grain of dust, although microscopic dimensions have yet to be realized.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Sensor node cost is similarly variable, ranging from a few to hundreds of dollars, depending on node sophistication.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Size and cost constraints constrain resources such as energy, memory, computational speed and communications bandwidth.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] The topology of a WSN can vary from a simple star network to an advanced multi-hop wireless mesh network.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Propagation can employ routing or flooding.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] As of 2010, wireless sensor networks had deployed approximately 120 million remote units worldwide.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Area monitoring is a common application of WSNs.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] In area monitoring, the WSN is deployed over a region where some phenomenon is to be monitored.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] A military example is the use of sensors to detect enemy intrusion; a civilian example is the geo-fencing of gas or oil pipelines.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] There are several types of sensor networks for medical applications: implanted, wearable, and environment-embedded.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Implantable medical devices are those that are inserted inside the human body.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Wearable devices are used on the body surface of a human or just at close proximity of the user.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Environment-embedded systems employ sensors contained in the environment.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Possible applications include body position measurement, location of persons, overall monitoring of ill patients in hospitals and at home.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Devices embedded in the environment track the physical state of a person for continuous health diagnosis, using as input the data from a network of depth cameras, a sensing floor, or other similar devices.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Body-area networks can collect information about an individual's health, fitness, and energy expenditure.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] In health care applications the privacy and authenticity of user data has prime importance.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Especially due to the integration of sensor networks, with IoT, the user authentication becomes more challenging; however, a solution is presented in recent work.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks have been used to monitor various species and habitats, beginning with the Great Duck Island Deployment, including marmots, cane toads in Australia and zebras in Kenya.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] There are many applications in monitoring environmental parameters, examples of which are given below.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] They share the extra challenges of harsh environments and reduced power supply.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Experiments have shown that personal exposure to air pollution in cities can vary a lot.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Therefore, it is of interest to have higher temporal and spatial resolution of pollutants and particulates.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] For research purposes, wireless sensor networks have been deployed to monitor the concentration of dangerous gases for citizens (e.g., in London).
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] However, sensors for gases and particulate matter suffer from high unit-to-unit variability, cross-sensitivities, and (concept) drift.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Moreover, the quality of data is currently insufficient for trustworthy decision-making, as field calibration leads to unreliable measurement results, and frequent recalibration might be required.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] A possible solution could be blind calibration or the usage of mobile references.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] A network of Sensor Nodes can be installed in a forest to detect when a fire has started.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] The nodes can be equipped with sensors to measure temperature, humidity and gases which are produced by fire in the trees or vegetation.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] The early detection is crucial for a successful action of the firefighters; thanks to Wireless Sensor Networks, the fire brigade will be able to know when a fire is started and how it is spreading.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] A landslide detection system makes use of a wireless sensor network to detect the slight movements of soil and changes in various parameters that may occur before or during a landslide.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Through the data gathered it may be possible to know the impending occurrence of landslides long before it actually happens.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Water quality monitoring involves analyzing water properties in dams, rivers, lakes and oceans, as well as underground water reserves.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] The use of many wireless distributed sensors enables the creation of a more accurate map of the water status, and allows the permanent deployment of monitoring stations in locations of difficult access, without the need of manual data retrieval.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks can be effective in preventing adverse consequences of natural disasters, like floods.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless nodes have been deployed successfully in rivers, where changes in water levels must be monitored in real time.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks have been developed for machinery condition-based maintenance (CBM) as they offer significant cost savings and enable new functionality.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensors can be placed in locations difficult or impossible to reach with a wired system, such as rotating machinery and untethered vehicles.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks also are used for the collection of data for monitoring of environmental information.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] This can be as simple as monitoring the temperature in a fridge or the level of water in overflow tanks in nuclear power plants.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] The statistical information can then be used to show how systems have been working.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] The advantage of WSNs over conventional loggers is the "live" data feed that is possible.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Monitoring the quality and level of water includes many activities such as checking the quality of underground or surface water and ensuring a country's water infrastructure for the benefit of both human and animal.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] It may be used to protect the wastage of water.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] WSN can be used to monitor the condition of civil infrastructure and related geo-physical processes close to real time, and over long periods through data logging, using appropriately interfaced sensors.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks are used to monitor wine production, both in the field and the cellar.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] The Wide Area Tracking System (WATS) is a prototype network for detecting a ground-based nuclear device such as a nuclear "briefcase bomb".
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] WATS is being developed at the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory (LLNL).
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] WATS would be made up of wireless gamma and neutron sensors connected through a communications network.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Data picked up by the sensors undergoes "data fusion", which converts the information into easily interpreted forms; this data fusion is the most important aspect of the system.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] The data fusion process occurs *within* the sensor network rather than at a centralized computer and is performed by a specially developed algorithm based on Bayesian statistics.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] WATS would not use a centralized computer for analysis because researchers found that factors such as latency and available bandwidth tended to create significant bottlenecks.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Data processed in the field by the network itself (by transferring small amounts of data between neighboring sensors) is faster and makes the network more scalable.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] An important factor in WATS development is *ease of deployment*, since more sensors both improves the detection rate and reduces false alarms.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] WATS sensors could be deployed in permanent positions or mounted in vehicles for mobile protection of specific locations.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] One barrier to the implementation of WATS is the size, weight, energy requirements and cost of currently available wireless sensors.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] The development of improved sensors is a major component of current research at the Nonproliferation, Arms Control, and International Security (NAI) Directorate at LLNL.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] House of Representatives' Military Research and Development Subcommittee on October 1, 1997, during a hearing on nuclear terrorism and countermeasures.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] On August 4, 1998, in a subsequent meeting of that subcommittee, Chairman Curt Weldon stated that research funding for WATS had been cut by the Clinton administration to a subsistence level and that the program had been poorly re-organized.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Studies show that using sensors for incident monitoring improve the response of firefighters and police to an unexpected situation.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] For an early detection of incidents we can use acoustic sensors to detect a spike in the noise of the city because of a possible accident, or use termic sensors to detect a possible fire.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Using low-power electronics, WSN:s can be cost-efficiently applied also in supply chains in various industries.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Cross-layer is becoming an important studying area for wireless communications.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] The traditional layered approach does not have the ability to adapt to the environmental change.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Because of the interference between the different users, access conflicts, fading, and the change of environment in the wireless sensor networks, traditional layered approach for wired networks is not applicable to wireless networks.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] So the cross-layer can be used to make the optimal modulation to improve the transmission performance, such as data rate, energy efficiency, quality of service (QoS), etc.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Sensor nodes can be imagined as small computers which are extremely basic in terms of their interfaces and their components.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] They usually consist of a *processing unit* with limited computational power and limited memory, *sensors* or MEMS (including specific conditioning circuitry), a *communication device* (usually radio transceivers or alternatively optical), and a power source usually in the form of a battery.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Other possible inclusions are energy harvesting modules, secondary ASICs, and possibly secondary communication interface (e.g.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] The base stations are one or more components of the WSN with much more computational, energy and communication resources.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] They act as a gateway between sensor nodes and the end user as they typically forward data from the WSN on to a server.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Other special components in routing based networks are routers, designed to compute, calculate and distribute the routing tables.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] One major challenge in a WSN is to produce *low cost* and *tiny* sensor nodes.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] There are an increasing number of small companies producing WSN hardware and the commercial situation can be compared to home computing in the 1970s.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Many of the nodes are still in the research and development stage, particularly their software.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Also inherent to sensor network adoption is the use of very low power methods for radio communication and data acquisition.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] In many applications, a WSN communicates with a local area network or wide area network through a gateway.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] The Gateway acts as a bridge between the WSN and the other network.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] This enables data to be stored and processed by devices with more resources, for example, in a remotely located server.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] A wireless wide area network used primarily for low-power devices is known as a Low-Power Wide-Area Network (LPWAN).
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] There are several wireless standards and solutions for sensor node connectivity.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Thread and Zigbee can connect sensors operating at 2.4 GHz with a data rate of 250 kbit/s.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Many use a lower frequency to increase radio range (typically 1 km), for example Z-wave operates at 915 MHz (in North America) and in the EU 868 MHz has been widely used but these have a lower data rate (typically 50 kbit/s).
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] The IEEE 802.15.4 working group provides a standard for low power device connectivity and commonly sensors and smart meters use one of these standards for connectivity.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] With the emergence of Internet of Things, many other proposals have been made to provide sensor connectivity.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] LoRa is a form of LPWAN which provides long range low power wireless connectivity for devices, which has been used in smart meters and other long range sensor applications.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] NarrowBand IOT and LTE-M can connect up to millions of sensors and devices using cellular technology.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Energy is the scarcest resource of WSN nodes, and it determines the lifetime of WSNs.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] WSNs may be deployed in large numbers in various environments, including remote and hostile regions, where ad hoc communications are a key component.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Lifetime maximization: Energy/Power Consumption of the sensing device should be minimized and sensor nodes should be energy efficient since their limited energy resource determines their lifetime.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] To conserve power, wireless sensor nodes normally power off both the radio transmitter and the radio receiver when not in use.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks are composed of low-energy, small-size, and low-range unattended sensor nodes.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Recently, it has been observed that by periodically turning on and off the sensing and communication capabilities of sensor nodes, we can significantly reduce the active time and thus prolong network lifetime.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] However, this duty cycling may result in high network latency, routing overhead, and neighbor discovery delays due to asynchronous sleep and wake-up scheduling.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] These limitations call for a countermeasure for duty-cycled wireless sensor networks which should minimize routing information, routing traffic load, and energy consumption.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Researchers from Sungkyunkwan University have proposed a lightweight non-increasing delivery-latency interval routing referred as LNDIR.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] This scheme can discover minimum latency routes at each non-increasing delivery-latency interval instead of each time slot.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Simulation experiments demonstrated the validity of this novel approach in minimizing routing information stored at each sensor.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Furthermore, this novel routing can also guarantee the minimum delivery latency from each source to the sink.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Performance improvements of up to 12-fold and 11-fold are observed in terms of routing traffic load reduction and energy efficiency, respectively, as compared to existing schemes.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Operating systems for wireless sensor network nodes are typically less complex than general-purpose operating systems.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] They more strongly resemble embedded systems, for two reasons.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] First, wireless sensor networks are typically deployed with a particular application in mind, rather than as a general platform.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Second, a need for low costs and low power leads most wireless sensor nodes to have low-power microcontrollers ensuring that mechanisms such as virtual memory are either unnecessary or too expensive to implement.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] It is therefore possible to use embedded operating systems such as eCos or uC/OS for sensor networks.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] However, such operating systems are often designed with real-time properties.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] TinyOS, developed by David Culler, is perhaps the first operating system specifically designed for wireless sensor networks.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] TinyOS is based on an event-driven programming model instead of multithreading.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] TinyOS programs are composed of *event handlers* and *tasks* with run-to-completion semantics.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] When an external event occurs, such as an incoming data packet or a sensor reading, TinyOS signals the appropriate event handler to handle the event.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Event handlers can post tasks that are scheduled by the TinyOS kernel some time later.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] LiteOS is a newly developed OS for wireless sensor networks, which provides UNIX-like abstraction and support for the C programming language.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Contiki, developed by Adam Dunkels, is an OS which uses a simpler programming style in C while providing advances such as 6LoWPAN and Protothreads.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] RIOT (operating system) is a more recent real-time OS including similar functionality to Contiki.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] PreonVM is an OS for wireless sensor networks, which provides 6LoWPAN based on Contiki and support for the Java programming language.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Examples include Xively and the Wikisensing platform Archived 2021-06-09 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Such platforms simplify online collaboration between users over diverse data sets ranging from energy and environment data to that collected from transport services.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Other services include allowing developers to embed real-time graphs & widgets in websites; analyse and process historical data pulled from the data feeds; send real-time alerts from any datastream to control scripts, devices and environments.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] At present, agent-based modeling and simulation is the only paradigm which allows the simulation of complex behavior in the environments of wireless sensors (such as flocking).
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Agent-based simulation of wireless sensor and ad hoc networks is a relatively new paradigm.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Agent-based modelling was originally based on social simulation.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Network simulators like Opnet, Tetcos NetSim and NS can be used to simulate a wireless sensor network.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Network localization refers to the problem of estimating the location of wireless sensor nodes during deployments and in dynamic settings.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] For ultra-low power sensors, size, cost and environment precludes the use of Global Positioning System receivers on sensors.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] In 2000, Nirupama Bulusu, John Heidemann and Deborah Estrin first motivated and proposed a radio connectivity based system for localization of wireless sensor networks.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Subsequently, such localization systems have been referred to as range free localization systems, and many localization systems for wireless sensor networks have been subsequently proposed including AHLoS, APS, and Stardust.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Sensors and devices used in wireless sensor networks are state-of-the-art technology with the lowest possible price.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] The sensor measurements we get from these devices are therefore often noisy, incomplete and inaccurate.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Researchers studying wireless sensor networks hypothesize that much more information can be extracted from hundreds of unreliable measurements spread across a field of interest than from a smaller number of high-quality, high-reliability instruments with the same total cost.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Macro-programming is a term coined by Matt Welsh.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] It refers to programming the entire sensor network as an ensemble, rather than individual sensor nodes.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Another way to macro-program a network is to view the sensor network as a database, which was popularized by the TinyDB system developed by Sam Madden.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Reprogramming is the process of updating the code on the sensor nodes.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] The most feasible form of reprogramming is remote reprogramming whereby the code is disseminated wirelessly while the nodes are deployed.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Different reprogramming protocols exist that provide different levels of speed of operation, reliability, energy expenditure, requirement of code resident on the nodes, suitability to different wireless environments, resistance to DoS, etc.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Infrastructure-less architecture (i.e. no gateways are included, etc.) and inherent requirements (i.e. unattended working environment, etc.) of WSNs might pose several weak points that attract adversaries.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Therefore, security is a big concern when WSNs are deployed for special applications such as military and healthcare.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Owing to their unique characteristics, traditional security methods of computer networks would be useless (or less effective) for WSNs.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Hence, lack of security mechanisms would cause intrusions towards those networks.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] These intrusions need to be detected and mitigation methods should be applied.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] There have been important innovations in securing wireless sensor networks.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Most wireless embedded networks use omni-directional antennas and therefore neighbors can overhear communication in and out of nodes.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] This was used this to develop a primitive called "*local monitoring*" which was used for detection of sophisticated attacks, like blackhole or wormhole, which degrade the throughput of large networks to close-to-zero.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] This primitive has since been used by many researchers and commercial wireless packet sniffers.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] This was subsequently refined for more sophisticated attacks such as with collusion, mobility, and multi-antenna, multi-channel devices.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] If a centralized architecture is used in a sensor network and the central node fails, then the entire network will collapse, however the reliability of the sensor network can be increased by using a distributed control architecture.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] To provide nodes with backup in case of failure of the central node.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] There is also no centralised body to allocate the resources and they have to be self organized.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] The data gathered from wireless sensor networks is usually saved in the form of numerical data in a central base station.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] To reduce communication costs some algorithms remove or reduce nodes' redundant sensor information and avoid forwarding data that is of no use.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] This technique has been used, for instance, for distributed anomaly detection or distributed optimization.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] As nodes can inspect the data they forward, they can measure averages or directionality for example of readings from other nodes.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] For example, in sensing and monitoring applications, it is generally the case that neighboring sensor nodes monitoring an environmental feature typically register similar values.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] This kind of data redundancy due to the spatial correlation between sensor observations inspires techniques for in-network data aggregation and mining.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Aggregation reduces the amount of network traffic which helps to reduce energy consumption on sensor nodes.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] This is a form of in-network processing where sensor nodes are assumed to be unsecured with limited available energy, while the base station is assumed to be secure with unlimited available energy.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Aggregation complicates the already existing security challenges for wireless sensor networks and requires new security techniques tailored specifically for these scenarios.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Providing security to aggregate data in wireless sensor networks is known as *secure data aggregation in WSN*. were the first few works discussing techniques for secure data aggregation in wireless sensor networks.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Two main security challenges in secure data aggregation are confidentiality and integrity of data.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] While encryption is traditionally used to provide end to end confidentiality in wireless sensor network, the aggregators in a secure data aggregation scenario need to decrypt the encrypted data to perform aggregation.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] This exposes the plaintext at the aggregators, making the data vulnerable to attacks from an adversary.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Similarly an aggregator can inject false data into the aggregate and make the base station accept false data.
[src:riot-os/wireless-sensor-network] Thus, while data aggregation improves energy efficiency of a network, it complicates the existing security challenges.
